{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 16:28:06.457371", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Summary\\n- Overall data-plane health: Good. Host-to-host reachability tests (pings) across the lab succeeded with 0% loss and acceptable RTTs — no evidence of packet loss or forwarding failure.\\n- Control-plane (BGP): All eBGP sessions between super-spine, spine and leaf routers are established. Routes for the expected /24 host subnets are present in routing tables on all routers.\\n- Anomaly detected: inconsistent BGP prefix counts between super-spine and its spine peers. This points to a control-plane discrepancy localized at the super-spine side (super_spine_router_0) or in the BGP session/processing there.\\n\\nWhat I checked (commands run / data gathered)\\n- End-to-end reachability: aggregated ping/reachability output (multiple host pairs).\\n- BGP running configurations on:\\n  - super_spine_router_0\\n  - spine_router_0_0\\n  - spine_router_0_1\\n  - leaf_router_0_0\\n  - leaf_router_0_1\\n- IP routing tables on the same five routers.\\n- BGP summary (show ip bgp summary) on the five routers.\\n\\nKey findings / evidence\\n\\n1) Data-plane (host pings)\\n- Reachability tests: all tested host pairs succeeded, 0% loss. Example entries (from supplied aggregated results):\\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_2_7: tx 2 rx 2 loss 0.0%, rtt_avg 8.003 ms\\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_3_0: tx 2 rx 2 loss 0.0%, rtt_avg 5.524 ms\\n- Conclusion: forwarding is working end-to-end.\\n\\n2) BGP sessions: sessions established and routes present\\n- All expected eBGP neighbors are Up on each router (super shows ~32 neighbors, spines/leafs show neighbors Up).\\n- The routing tables show BGP routes for the /24s (10.0.x.x..10.3.x.x). Example from super_spine_router_0\\'s routing table:\\n  - B>* 10.0.0.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.0.1, eth0\\n  - B>* 10.3.7.0/24 [20/0] via 172.16.0.49, eth24\\n- Conclusion: route exchange is occurring and subnets are installed into RIB/FIB.\\n\\n3) BGP prefix-count inconsistency (the main anomaly)\\n- On super_spine_router_0 (show ip bgp summary) many neighbors show PfxRcd = 8 and PfxSnt = 32 (example excerpt):\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.1 (AS 65100): MsgRcvd 38 MsgSent 38 … State/PfxRcd = 8 PfxSnt = 32\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.3 (AS 65101): … PfxRcd = 8 PfxSnt = 32\\n  - (multiple other neighbors show the same PfxRcd = 8)\\n- On the corresponding spine routers the summary for the super-spine neighbor shows the spines claim they have sent many more prefixes to the super-spine. Example from spine_router_0_0:\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.0 (super_spine_router_0) shows PfxRcd = 24 and PfxSnt = 32 (spine\\'s view of the super <-> spine relationship)\\n  - spine_router_0_1 similarly shows PfxSnt values of 32 to the super and PfxRcd values larger than 8 for some neighbors.\\n- In plain terms: the spine routers report that they have sent ~32 prefixes to the super-spine, but the super-spine reports it has received only 8 prefixes from those same spine neighbors. That mismatch is visible across multiple spine neighbors.\\n\\n4) Additional signals\\n- Some neighbors on the super show higher-than-average MsgRcvd values (e.g., 61) compared to others (38). This suggests some neighbors have generated more update traffic recently — could be related to route refreshes or repeated updates.\\n- super_spine_router_0 router-id is configured as 172.16.0.0 (unusual but permitted). The configuration does not show explicit route-maps or prefix-lists being applied to neighbors in the snippet returned (super_spine config lists neighbors but no explicit inbound prefix filter lines were present in the running-config output returned).\\n\\nLocalization of fault\\n- The discrepancy is localized to the super-spine side of the super-spine <-> spine adjacencies:\\n  - The spine routers claim they are advertising (sending) ~32 prefixes to the super-spine.\\n  - The super-spine\\'s BGP summary counters indicate it has only recorded receiving 8 prefixes from those spine neighbors.\\n- Therefore the control-plane discrepancy is observed at super_spine_router_0 (or in how super_spine_router_0 is processing/recording the prefixes from its spine neighbors).\\n\\nLikely root-cause hypotheses (based on the evidence)\\n- BGP attribute/AFI-SAFI or session negotiation issue: partial route-family negotiation leading to only a subset of prefixes being accepted/installed on the super-spine for the IPv4-unicast AFI/SAFI.\\n- Local filtering/route-policy on super_spine_router_0 (inbound filters or prefix-lists) silently limiting accepted prefixes. The running-config excerpt shown did not include explicit prefix-lists, but policies could exist elsewhere or be applied via default policy mechanisms or in VRF/AF sections not returned.\\n- BGP route processing bug or counter inconsistency in FRR: the counters displayed in \"show ip bgp summary\" on super_spine_router_0 could be inaccurate (i.e., a metrics/counters bug) while the actual RIB contains the expected prefixes. However, the routing table on super_spine does show many 10.x prefixes — the mismatch is specifically between per-peer PfxRcd counters and peer-reported PfxSnt counters.\\n- Route reflection or AS-path/policy behavior leading to selective advertisement: some spines may be sending prefixes but with attributes that cause the super to not accept them as distinct prefixes (for example, if routes are suppressed due to next-hop unreachable or as-path filtering).\\n- Excessive updates / flapping from some neighbors (higher MsgRcvd counts) causing transient state where not all prefixes are stably recorded at the super\\'s peer-level counters.\\n\\nWhy this matters\\n- Even though current data-plane tests show good forwarding, a persistent control-plane discrepancy (super-spine not seeing the full set of prefixes from spines) can lead to incomplete topology visibility, suboptimal routing, or future reachability gaps if the super does not have a full view of prefixes it should be distributing/processing.\\n\\nConcrete evidence excerpts (representative)\\n- super_spine_router_0 (BGP summary lines):\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.1 … State/PfxRcd = 8 PfxSnt = 32\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.3 … State/PfxRcd = 8 PfxSnt = 32\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.57 … MsgRcvd 61 MsgSent 37\\n- spine_router_0_0 (BGP summary line):\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.0 (super) … PfxRcd = 24 PfxSnt = 32\\n- Routing table on super_spine_router_0:\\n  - Many BGP routes for 10.0.0.0/24..10.3.7.0/24 are present (so many prefixes do exist in the table).\\n\\nRecommended next diagnostic steps (if you want to proceed)\\n- (If you request further investigation) gather:\\n  - Per-neighbor \"show ip bgp neighbors X.X.X.X\" output on both super_spine_router_0 and a representative spine to compare exact prefixes received/sent, received updates, route-refresh events and any prefix-list/filters applied.\\n  - BGP debug/logs on super_spine_router_0 around the time of session establishment (look at the frr log entries for routes being accepted/rejected).\\n  - Check AFI/SAFI negotiation and address-family configuration on super_spine and spines (explicit address-family stanza differences).\\n  - Verify there are no implicit VRF/prefix-lists or route-policy applied elsewhere in the device config that were not included in the config trims returned.\\n\\nBottom-line diagnosis\\n- Data-plane (host reachability): healthy.\\n- Control-plane: established BGP sessions and routes present, but an inconsistency in per-peer BGP prefix counts is present — super_spine_router_0 reports receiving far fewer prefixes from its spine neighbors than the spines report they sent. The control-plane discrepancy is localized to super_spine_router_0 and likely caused by either local filtering/policy, an AFI/SAFI negotiation mismatch, or an FRR control-plane counter/processing anomaly.\\n\\nIf you want, I can continue with targeted commands (per-neighbor BGP detail, logs, or AFI/SAFI checks) to narrow the root cause further., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='b5ca597b-2d21-40c0-806c-75db79a0f4d3'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
